using the include macro, will display the content of the desired page as it is. i.e. a level 1 heading (h1) on a "sub"page will result in a h1 displayed on the page {include} was used.

If you want to include certain pages beyond a self defined h1. all upcoming h1. from the subpages are on the same heading level.

*Example:*
Page1:
{code}
{include:page2}
{code}

Page2:
{code}
h1. my heading
h2. sub heading
...
{code}

Result on page1:
{code}
h1. my heading
h2. sub heading
...
{code}

So it is quite ok up to here.

To my opinion, we need a parameter "_minLevel_" and "_heading_" for the include macro:
*Example 2:*
Page1:
{code}
h1. some heading on page1
,,,

h1. Topic of page2 
{include:page2}
{code}

Unexpected result on page1:
{code}
h1. some heading on page1
,,,

h1. Topic of page2 
h1. my heading
h2. sub heading
...
{code}

^^ All headings from page 2 should be decremented one level

*Example 2 with "minLevel":*
Page1:
{code}
h1. some heading on page1
,,,

h1. Topic of page2 
{include:page2|minLevel=2}
{code}

Expected result on page1:
{code}
h1. some heading on page1
,,,

h1. Topic of page2 
h2. my heading
h3. sub heading
...
{code}


*Example 2 with "heading":*
Page1:
{code}
h1. some heading on page1
,,,

{include:page2|minLevel=2|heading=Topic of page2}
{code}

expected result on page1:
{code}
h1. some heading on page1
,,,

h1. Topic of page2 
h2. my heading
h3. sub heading
...
{code}

I don't know, if the combination of minLevel and heading is the best solution, but will show up want I intend to do here ;)

Thank you and with kind regards,
~Marcel

